{
  "monologue": "The user shows moderate progress but ongoing stress-related triggers. They respond best to ultra-simple, repeatable micro-actions that reinforce structure. A quick urge-check-in paired with a tiny non-food action leverages CBT principles (urge labeling, cue exposure, and behavioral activation) without adding cognitive load, supporting progression toward the target behavior level while honoring their need for routine.",
  "utterance": "Nice work tonight. After your 3-minute reset, add a quick urge-check-in: in about 60 seconds, name the trigger in a word or two and rate the urge on a 0â€“5 scale, then immediately pick one non-food action from this tiny kit and do it before you log your mood. Options: sip a glass of water, stand and march in place for 60 seconds, or do a brief body-grounding breath (30 seconds) plus a quick scan of how your body feels. Then log your urge and mood to track the impact. Keeping this ultra-simple supports your need for structure and helps curb stress-driven urges.",
  "endkey": false
}
